medical_history.chief_complaint: Ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome during the fifth spontaneous pregnancy.
medical_history.history_of_present_illness: The symptoms were first suspected after a therapeutic abortion at eight weeks’ gestation of the first pregnancy, presenting with abdominal pain and nausea. The syndrome was recurrent in her subsequent pregnancies, initially detected at eight weeks during the third pregnancy and persisting throughout. The current episode involved acute lower abdominal pain and nausea during the eighth week of the fifth pregnancy.
medical_history.past_medical_history: She had a history of recurrent ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome in all but one of her pregnancies.
medical_history.family_history: Two of the patient’s four sisters reported similar histories of ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome during their pregnancies, but it was inconsistent among them.
